Definition 2.3. Let $s,t:\sigma^{*}$. We say that $s$ and $t$ are extensionally equal, and write $s=_{e}t$, if $|s|=|t|\land\forall i<|s|\,(s_{i}=t_{i})\;.$
Definition 3.8. We will denote the topos $\mathrm{Sh}(\mathfrak{F}\mathbf{Set},K)$ by $\mathcal{N}$, for nonstandard universe.
Definition 2.9. The system E-HA${}^{\omega*}_{\mathrm{st}}$ is an extension of E-HA${}^{\omega*}$, whose language includes a (unary) predicate $\mathrm{st}_{\sigma}(x)$, $x:\sigma$, for all types $\sigma$ of $\mathbf{T}^{*}$; and the external quantifiers $\forall^{\mathrm{st}}x:\sigma$, $\exists^{\mathrm{st}}x:\sigma$. Notation. Following Nelson, so-called internal formulae - those in the language of E-HA${}^{\omega*}$ - are always denoted with small Greek letters, and generic, external formulae with capital Greek letters. The following axioms are added to those of E-HA${}^{\omega*}$: 1. the defining axioms of the external quantifiers: $\displaystyle\forall^{\mathrm{st}}x:\sigma\,\Phi(x)\leftrightarrow\forall x:% \sigma\,(\mathrm{st}_{\sigma}(x)\to\Phi(x))\;,$ $\displaystyle\exists^{\mathrm{st}}x:\sigma\,\Phi(x)\leftrightarrow\exists x:% \sigma\,(\mathrm{st}_{\sigma}(x)\land\Phi(x))\;;$ 2. axioms for the standardness predicate: $\begin{matrix}[l]&\mathrm{st}_{\sigma}(x)\land x=_{\sigma}y\to\mathrm{st}_{% \sigma}(y)\;,\\ &\mathrm{st}_{\sigma}(a)&\text{for all \emph{closed} }a:\sigma\;,\\ &\mathrm{st}_{\sigma\to\tau}(f)\land\mathrm{st}_{\sigma}(x)\to\mathrm{st}_{% \tau}(fx)\;;\end{matrix}$ 3. the external induction schema: $\mathsf{IA}^{\mathrm{st}}:\quad\big{(}\Phi(0)\land\forall^{\mathrm{st}}x:0\,(% \Phi(x)\to\Phi(\mathrm{S}x))\big{)}\to\forall^{\mathrm{st}}x:0\,\Phi(x)\;.$ Since it is part of E-HA${}^{\omega*}$, the system E-HA${}^{\omega*}_{\mathrm{st}}$ also contains, besides the external induction schema, an “internal” induction schema $\mathsf{IA}$, which is assumed to hold for internal formulae only.
Definition 2.6 (Finite sequence application and abstraction). Let $s:(\sigma\to\tau^{*})^{*}$, $a:\sigma$, $t:\tau^{*}$. Then $\displaystyle s[a]$ $\displaystyle:=(s_{0}a)\cdot\ldots\cdot(s_{|s|-1}a):\tau^{*}\;,$ $\displaystyle\Lambda x:\sigma.t$ $\displaystyle:=C(\lambda x:\sigma.t)\langle\rangle:(\sigma\to\tau^{*})^{*}\;.$
Definition 2.17. A formula $\Phi(s)$ is upwards closed in $s:\sigma^{*}$ if $\Phi(s)\land s\subseteq s^{\prime}\to\Phi(s^{\prime})\;.$
Definition 3.2. A filter base $\mathcal{F}_{I}$ on $S$ is an inhabited set $\{\mathcal{F}_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ of elements of $S$, such that, for all $i,j\in I$, there exists $k\in I$ such that $\mathcal{F}_{k}\leq\mathcal{F}_{i}\land\mathcal{F}_{j}$. A filter base generates a filter, as follows: $A$ belongs to the filter if and only if there exists $i\in I$ such that $\mathcal{F}_{i}\leq A$.
Definition 4.11. The Grothendieck topos $\mathrm{Sh}(\mathfrak{F}\mathbf{Set},K_{1})$ will be called $\mathcal{U}$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathbf{C}$ be a finitely complete category. The filter category $\mathfrak{F}\mathbf{C}$ over $\mathbf{C}$ is described by the following data. • Objects are pairs $(C,\mathcal{F}_{I})$, where $C$ is an object of $\mathbf{C}$, and $\mathcal{F}_{I}$ is an $I$-indexed filter base on $\mathrm{Sub}(C)$. We will usually write $\mathcal{F}$ for $(C,\mathcal{F}_{I})$, when the underlying object and indexing set are not relevant, and just call it a filter. We say that the $\mathcal{F}_{i}$, $i\in I$, are the base objects of the filter. • Morphisms are “germs of continuous morphisms”. A continuous morphism $\alpha:(C,\mathcal{F}_{I})\to(D,\mathcal{G}_{J})$ is a partial morphism $\tikzcd[columnsep=3ex,rowsep=3ex]&\mathcal{F}_{i}\arrow[tail]{dl}\arrow{dr}{% \alpha}&\\ C&&D$ in $\mathbf{C}$, defined on some base object $\mathcal{F}_{i}$, such that for all $j\in J$, there exists $i^{\prime}\in I$ such that $\mathcal{F}_{i^{\prime}}\leq\alpha^{*}\mathcal{G}_{j}$ in $\mathrm{Sub}(C)$. We declare two such morphisms $\alpha:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to D$, $\alpha^{\prime}:\mathcal{F}_{j}\to D$ equivalent if there exists $k\in I$ such that $\mathcal{F}_{k}\leq\mathcal{F}_{i}\land\mathcal{F}_{j}$, and ${\left.\kern-1.2pt\alpha\vphantom{\big{|}}\right|_{\mathcal{F}_{k}}}={\left.% \kern-1.2pt\alpha^{\prime}\vphantom{\big{|}}\right|_{\mathcal{F}_{k}}}$; that is, the following pullback square commutes: $\tikzcd\mathcal{F}_{k}\arrow[tail]{r}\arrow[tail]{d}&\mathcal{F}_{i}\arrow{d}{% \alpha}\\ \mathcal{F}_{j}\arrow{r}{\alpha^{\prime}}&D\;.$ We have an embedding of $\mathbf{C}$ into $\mathfrak{F}\mathbf{C}$, where an object $C$ of $\mathbf{C}$ is identified with the “simple” filter $(C,\{C\})$. We will usually still denote the latter with $C$.
Definition 2.19. Let $s:\sigma^{*}$. We say that $s$ is a hyperfinite enumeration of the type $\sigma$ if $\forall^{\mathrm{st}}x:\sigma\,(x\in s)\;.$ We define, for all types $\sigma$, a predicate $\mathrm{hyper}(s):=\forall^{\mathrm{st}}x:\sigma\,(x\in s)\;,$ as well as quantifiers ranging over hyperfinite enumerations, with defining axioms $\displaystyle\forall^{\mathrm{hyp}}s:\sigma^{*}\,\Phi(s):=\forall s:\sigma^{*}% \,(\mathrm{hyper}_{\sigma}(s)\to\Phi(s))\;,$ $\displaystyle\exists^{\mathrm{hyp}}s:\sigma^{*}\,\Phi(s):=\exists s:\sigma^{*}% \,(\mathrm{hyper}_{\sigma}(s)\land\Phi(s))\;.$
Definition 4.3. To every formula $\Phi(\underline{a})$ of the language of E-HA${}^{\omega*}_{\mathrm{st}\lor})$, with free variables $\underline{a}$, we associate inductively its uniform Diller-Nahm translation $\Phi(\underline{a})^{U}=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{x}\,\forall^{\mathrm{% st}}\underline{y}\,\varphi_{U}(\underline{x},\underline{y},\underline{a})$, where $\varphi_{U}$ is internal and $\lor$-free. $\triangleright$ $\varphi(\underline{a})^{U}:=\varphi_{U}(\underline{a}):=\varphi(\underline{a})$, for $\varphi$ internal atomic; $\triangleright$ $\mathrm{st}_{\sigma}(x)^{U}:=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}y:\sigma\,(y=x)\;$. Let $\Phi(\underline{a})^{U}=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{x}\,\forall^{\mathrm{% st}}\underline{y}\,\varphi_{U}(\underline{x},\underline{y},\underline{a})$, $\Psi(\underline{b})^{U}=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{u}\,\forall^{\mathrm{% st}}\underline{v}\,\psi_{U}(\underline{u},\underline{v},\underline{b})$: $\triangleright$ $(\Phi(\underline{a})\land\Psi(\underline{b}))^{U}:=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}% \underline{x},\underline{u}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y},\underline{v}% \,\big{(}\varphi_{U}(\underline{x},\underline{y},\underline{a})\land\psi_{U}(% \underline{u},\underline{v},\underline{b})\big{)}\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\Phi(\underline{a})\lor\Psi(\underline{b}))^{U}:=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}z:0,% \underline{x},\underline{u}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y},\underline{v}% \,\big{(}z=0\to\varphi_{U}(\underline{x},\underline{y},\underline{a})\land\neg% \,z=0\to\psi_{U}(\underline{u},\underline{v},\underline{b})\big{)}\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\Phi(\underline{a})\to\Psi(\underline{b}))^{U}:=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}% \underline{U},\underline{Y}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{x},\underline{v}% \,\big{(}\forall\underline{y}\in\underline{Y}\underline{x}\underline{v}\,% \varphi_{U}(\underline{x},\underline{y},\underline{a})\to\psi_{U}(\underline{U% }\underline{x},\underline{v},\underline{b})\big{)}\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\exists z\,\Phi(z,\underline{a}))^{U}:=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{x}\,% \forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y}\,\exists z\,\forall\underline{y}^{\prime}% \in\underline{y}\,\varphi_{U}(\underline{x},\underline{y}^{\prime},z,% \underline{a})\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\forall z\,\Phi(z,\underline{a}))^{U}:=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{x}\,% \forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y}\,\forall z\,\varphi_{U}(\underline{x},% \underline{y},z,\underline{a})\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\exists^{\mathrm{st}}z\,\Phi(z,\underline{a}))^{U}:=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}z,% \underline{x}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y}\,\varphi_{U}(\underline{x},% \underline{y},z,\underline{a})\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\forall^{\mathrm{st}}z\,\Phi(z,\underline{a}))^{U}:=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}% \underline{X}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y},z\,\varphi_{U}(\underline{X}% z,\underline{y},z,\underline{a})\;$.
Definition 3.1. Let $S$ be a $\land$-semilattice. A filter on $S$ is an inhabited, upwards closed subset of $S$ that is closed under binary meets. We say that a filter is proper if it does not coincide with $S$; otherwise, it is non proper.
Definition 2.16. To every formula $\Phi(\underline{a})$ of the language of E-HA${}^{\omega*}_{\mathrm{st}}$, with free variables $\underline{a}$, we associate inductively its nonstandard Dialectica translation $\Phi(\underline{a})^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{s}\,% \forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y}\,\varphi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline{s},% \underline{y},\underline{a})\;,$ where $\varphi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}$ is internal, and all the variables in $\underline{s}$ are of sequence type. $\triangleright$ $\varphi(\underline{a})^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}:=\varphi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline% {a}):=\varphi(\underline{a})$, for $\varphi$ internal atomic; $\triangleright$ $\mathrm{st}_{\sigma}(x)^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}:=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}s:\sigma^{*}\,% (x\in s)\;$. Let $\Phi(\underline{a})^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{s}\,% \forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y}\,\varphi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline{s},% \underline{y},\underline{a})$, $\Psi(\underline{b})^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{t}\,% \forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{v}\,\psi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline{t},% \underline{v},\underline{b})$: $\triangleright$ $(\Phi(\underline{a})\land\Psi(\underline{b}))^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}:=\exists^{% \mathrm{st}}\underline{s},\underline{t}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y},% \underline{v}\,\big{(}\varphi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline{s},\underline{y},% \underline{a})\land\psi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline{t},\underline{v},% \underline{b})\big{)}\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\Phi(\underline{a})\lor\Psi(\underline{b}))^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}:=\exists^{% \mathrm{st}}\underline{s},\underline{t}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y},% \underline{v}\,\big{(}\varphi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline{s},\underline{y},% \underline{a})\lor\psi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline{t},\underline{v},% \underline{b})\big{)}\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\Phi(\underline{a})\to\Psi(\underline{b}))^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}:=\exists^{% \mathrm{st}}\underline{T},\underline{Y}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{s},% \underline{v}\,\big{(}\forall\underline{y}\in\underline{Y}[\underline{s},% \underline{v}]\,\varphi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline{s},\underline{y},% \underline{a})\to\psi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline{T}[\underline{s}],% \underline{v},\underline{b})\big{)}\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\exists z\,\Phi(z,\underline{a}))^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}:=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}% \underline{s}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{t}\,\exists z\,\forall% \underline{y}\in\underline{t}\,\varphi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline{x},% \underline{y},z,\underline{a})\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\forall z\,\Phi(z,\underline{a}))^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}:=\exists^{\mathrm{st}}% \underline{s}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y}\,\forall z\,\varphi_{D_{% \mathrm{st}}}(\underline{s},\underline{y},z,\underline{a})\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\exists^{\mathrm{st}}z\,\Phi(z,\underline{a}))^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}:=\exists^{% \mathrm{st}}u,\underline{s}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{t}\,\exists z\in u% \,\forall\underline{y}\in\underline{t}\,\varphi_{D_{\mathrm{st}}}(\underline{s% },\underline{y},z,\underline{a})\;$; $\triangleright$ $(\forall^{\mathrm{st}}z\,\Phi(z,\underline{a}))^{D_{\mathrm{st}}}:=\exists^{% \mathrm{st}}\underline{S}\,\forall^{\mathrm{st}}\underline{y},z\,\varphi_{D_{% \mathrm{st}}}(\underline{S}[z],\underline{y},z,\underline{a})\;$.
Definition 2.5. Let $a:\sigma$, $s,s^{\prime}:\sigma^{*}$. We define the abbreviations (i) $a\in_{\sigma}s:=\exists i<|s|\,(a=_{\sigma}s_{i})$ ($a$ is an element of $s$); (ii) $s^{\prime}\subseteq_{\sigma}s:=\forall x:\sigma\,(x\in_{\sigma}s^{\prime}\to x% \in_{\sigma}s)$ ($s^{\prime}$ is contained in $s$). We will drop subscripts in most occasions. We also extend the relation $\subseteq_{\sigma}$ to sequence-valued functionals, pointwise: for $s^{\prime},s:\tau\to\sigma^{*}$, (iii) $s^{\prime}\subseteq s:=\forall x:\tau\,(s^{\prime}x\subseteq_{\sigma}sx)\;.$ The relation $\subseteq$ determines a preorder, provably in E-HA${}^{\omega*}$.
Definition B.1. For each each propagator $f^{(1)}\colon A\to B$, each list of exception names $(T_{1},\dots,T_{n})$ and each propagators $g_{j}^{(1)}\colon V_{i}\to B$ for $i=1,\dots,n$, the propagator $\mathtt{try}(f)\mathtt{catch}\,(T_{1}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{1}|\dots|T_{n}\!% \Rightarrow\!g_{n})^{(1)}\colon A\to B$ is defined as follows, in two steps: • the catcher $\mathtt{catch}\,(T_{1}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{1}|\dots|T_{n}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{n})^{(% 2)}:\mathbb{0}\to B$ is obtained by setting $i=1$ in the family of catchers $k_{i}^{(2)}=\mathtt{catch}\,(T_{i}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{i}|\dots|T_{n}\!% \Rightarrow\!g_{n}):\mathbb{0}\to B$ (for $i=1,\dots,n$) which are defined recursively by: $k_{i}^{(2)}\;=\;\begin{cases}[\;g_{n}^{(1)}\;|\;[\;]_{B}^{(0)}\;]^{(1)}\circ% \mathtt{untag}_{n}^{(2)}&\mbox{ when }i=n\\ [\;g_{i}^{(1)}\;|\;k_{i+1}^{(2)}\;]_{l}^{(2)}\circ\mathtt{untag}_{i}^{(2)}&% \mbox{ when }i<n\\ \end{cases}$ • then the required propagator is: $\begin{array}[]{l}\mathtt{try}(f)\mathtt{catch}\,(T_{1}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{1}|% \dots|T_{n}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{n})^{(1)}=\\ \qquad\qquad[\;\mathit{id}_{B}\;|\;\mathtt{catch}\,(T_{1}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{1}|% \dots|T_{n}\!\Rightarrow\!g_{n})\;]_{l}^{(2)}\odot f^{(1)}\colon A\to B\\ \end{array}$
Definition 4.1. A language with effects is compatible with conditionals when the category $\mathbf{C}$ has finite coproducts and when the copairs of general terms are defined: for each $f_{1}^{(g)}\colon A_{1}\to B$ and $f_{2}^{(g)}\colon A_{2}\to B$ there exists a unique $[f_{1}|f_{2}]^{(g)}\colon A_{1}+A_{2}\to B$ such that $[f_{1}|f_{2}]\circ\mathit{in}_{1}=f_{1}$ and $[f_{1}|f_{2}]\circ\mathit{in}_{2}=f_{2}$ (where $\mathit{in}_{1}^{(0)}\colon A_{1}\to A_{1}+A_{2}$ and $\mathit{in}_{2}^{(0)}\colon A_{2}\to A_{1}+A_{2}$ are the coprojections).
Definition 4.7. Let $v^{(0)}\colon A\to B$ be a pure term and $f^{(1)}\colon A\to B$ a propagator, corresponding respectively to $v_{0}\colon A\to B$ and $f_{1}\colon A\to B+E$ in $\mathbf{C}$. Then $v^{(0)}\gg f^{(1)}$ if and only if the restrictions of $v_{0}$ and $f_{1}$ to the domain of definition of $f_{1}$ coincide, which means, if and only if $v_{0}\circ i_{f}=f_{\mathit{normal}}\colon\mathcal{D}_{f}\to B$.
Definition 4.6. For each type $B$ and each exception name $T$, the propagator $\mathtt{throw}_{B,T}^{(1)}$ is: $\mathtt{throw}_{B,T}^{(1)}=[\;]_{B}^{(0)}\circ\mathtt{tag}_{T}^{(1)}\colon V_{% T}\to B$ For each each propagator $f^{(1)}\colon A\to B$, each exception name $T$ and each propagator $g^{(1)}\colon V_{T}\to B$, the propagator $\mathtt{try}(f)\mathtt{catch}(T\Rightarrow g)^{(1)}$ is defined as follows, in two steps: $\begin{array}[]{l}\mathtt{catch}(T\Rightarrow g)^{(2)}=[\;g^{(1)}\;|\;[\;]_{B}% ^{(0)}\;]^{(1)}\circ\mathtt{untag}_{T}^{(2)}\colon\mathbb{0}\to B\\ \mathtt{try}(f)\mathtt{catch}(T\Rightarrow g)^{(1)}=[\;\mathit{id}_{B}\;|\;% \mathtt{catch}(T\Rightarrow g)\;]_{l}^{(2)}\odot f^{(1)}\colon A\to B\\ \end{array}$
Definition B.2. For each propagators $f^{(1)}\colon A\to B$ and $g^{(1)}\colon\mathbb{1}\to B$, the propagator $\mathtt{try}(f)\mathtt{catch}(\mathtt{all}\Rightarrow g)^{(1)}\colon A\to B$ is: $\mathtt{try}(f)\mathtt{catch}(\mathtt{all}\Rightarrow g)^{(1)}=[\;\mathit{id}_% {B}\,|\,g\circ\mathtt{untag}_{\mathtt{all}}\;]_{l}^{(2)}\odot f^{(1)}\colon A\to B$
Definition 4.2. Let $\gg$ be a relation between pure terms and general terms which is the equality when both terms are pure. A language with effects is compatible with sequential pairs, with respect to $\gg$, when the category $\mathbf{C}$ has finite products and when the left and right pairs of a pure term and a general term are defined, in the following sense: for each $f_{1}^{(0)}\colon A\to B_{1}$ and $f_{2}^{(g)}\colon A\to B_{2}$ there exists a unique $\langle f_{1},f_{2}\rangle_{l}^{(g)}\colon A\to B_{1}\times B_{2}$ such that $\mathit{pr}_{1}\circ\langle f_{1},f_{2}\rangle_{l}\gg f_{1}$ and $\mathit{pr}_{2}\circ\langle f_{1},f_{2}\rangle_{l}=f_{2}$ (where $\mathit{pr}_{1}^{(0)}\colon B_{1}\times B_{2}\to B_{1}$ and $\mathit{pr}_{2}^{(0)}\colon B_{1}\times B_{2}\to B_{2}$ are the projections), and symmetrically for $\langle f_{1}^{(g)},f_{2}^{(0)}\rangle_{r}^{(g)}$.
Definition 4.8. Let $v^{(0)}\colon A\to B_{1}$ be a pure term and $f^{(1)}\colon A\to B_{2}$ a propagator, corresponding respectively to $v_{0}\colon A\to B_{1}$ and $f_{1}\colon A\to B_{2}+E$ in $\mathbf{C}$. Let $h_{\mathit{normal}}=\langle v\circ i_{f},f_{\mathit{normal}}\rangle\colon% \mathcal{D}_{g}\to B_{1}\times B_{2}$ and $h_{\mathit{abrupt}}=f_{\mathit{abrupt}}\colon\mathcal{E}_{g}\to E$, then let $h=h_{\mathit{normal}}+h_{\mathit{abrupt}}\colon A\to(B_{1}\times B_{2})+E$ in $\mathbf{C}$. The morphism $h$ in $\mathbf{C}$ corresponds to a propagator $h^{(1)}\colon A\to B_{1}\times B_{2}$, which is the interpretation of the left pair $\langle v,f\rangle_{l}^{(1)}$ of $v^{(0)}$ and $f^{(1)}$.
Definition 5.1. A set theoretic manifold over $\mathbb{K}$ is given by $(M,V,(U_{i},\phi_{i},V_{i})_{i\in I})$, where $M$ is a set, $V$ is a $\mathbb{K}$-module, and, for each $i$ belonging to an index set $I$, $U_{i}\subset M$ and $V_{i}\subset V$ are non-empty subsets such that $M=\cup_{i\in I}U_{i}$, and $\phi_{i}:U_{i}\to V_{i}$ is a set-theoretic isomorphism (bijection). We then also say that ${\mathcal{A}}=(U_{i},\phi_{i},V_{i})_{i\in I}$ is an atlas on $M$ with model space $V$, and we say that the topology generated by the sets $(U_{i})_{i\in I}$ on $M$ is the atlas-topology on $M$. The atlas is called saturated if the $U_{i}$ form a basis of the atlas-topology.
Definition 7.7. A (Weil) symmetric space is a Weil space with a binary Weil law $\underline{s}:\underline{M}\times\underline{M}\to\underline{M}$ such that, for each Weil algebra $\mathbb{A}$, (1) $\forall x\in M^{\mathbb{A}}$: $s^{\mathbb{A}}(x,x)=x$ (2) $\forall x,y\in M^{\mathbb{A}}$: $s^{\mathbb{A}}(x,s^{\mathbb{A}}(x,y))=y$ (3) $\forall x,y,z\in M$: $s^{\mathbb{A}}(x,s^{\mathbb{A}}(y,s^{\mathbb{A}}(x,z)))=s^{\mathbb{A}}(s^{% \mathbb{A}}(x,y),z)$ (4) $\forall x\in M^{\mathbb{A}}$, $y\in T_{x}(M^{\mathbb{A}})$: $s^{T\mathbb{A}}(0_{x},y)=-y$.
Definition 3.4. A subspace $\underline{U}$ of a Weil space $\underline{M}$ is a Weil space $\underline{U}$ such that, for each Weil algebra $\mathbb{A}$, $U^{\mathbb{A}}$ is a subset of $M^{\mathbb{A}}$. If each $U^{\mathbb{A}}$ is of cardinality $1$, then $\underline{U}$ is called a point in $\underline{M}$.
Definition 2.3. In the categories of bundle or Weil algebras, pushouts and pullbacks are given by the following constructions: given two algebras in these categories, $\mathbb{A}=\mathbb{K}\oplus{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}$ and $\mathbb{B}=\mathbb{K}\oplus{\mathring{\mathbb{B}}}$, (1) the pushout (with respect to the zero sections) is the tensor product over $\mathbb{K}$, which can be identified with the $\mathbb{K}$-module $\mathbb{A}\otimes_{\mathbb{K}}\mathbb{B}=(\mathbb{K}\oplus{\mathring{\mathbb{A% }}})\otimes_{\mathbb{K}}(\mathbb{K}\oplus{\mathring{\mathbb{B}}})=\mathbb{K}% \oplus({\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}\oplus{\mathring{\mathbb{B}}}\oplus{\mathring{% \mathbb{A}}}\otimes_{\mathbb{K}}{\mathring{\mathbb{B}}}),$ with product given by: $(x;a,b,u\otimes v)\cdot(x^{\prime};a^{\prime},b^{\prime},u^{\prime}\otimes v^{% \prime})=\bigl{(}xx^{\prime};xa^{\prime}+x^{\prime}a+aa^{\prime},$ $\qquad\qquad xb^{\prime}+x^{\prime}b+bb^{\prime},xu^{\prime}\otimes v^{\prime}% +x^{\prime}u\otimes v+uu^{\prime}\otimes vv^{\prime}+a\otimes b^{\prime}+a^{% \prime}\otimes b\bigr{)},$ (2) the pullback (with respect to the projections) is the fibered product or Whitney sum over $\mathbb{K}$, which can be identified with the $\mathbb{K}$-module $\mathbb{A}\times_{\mathbb{K}}\mathbb{B}=\mathbb{K}\oplus({\mathring{\mathbb{A}% }}\oplus{\mathring{\mathbb{B}}})$ with product given by: $(x;a,b)\cdot(x^{\prime};a^{\prime},b^{\prime})=(xx^{\prime};xa^{\prime}+x^{% \prime}a+aa^{\prime},xb^{\prime}+x^{\prime}b+bb^{\prime}).$
Definition 4.1 (N. Roby, [Ro63]). A polynomial law between two $\mathbb{K}$-modules $V$ and $W$ is a natural transformation $\underline{f}:\underline{\bf V}\to\underline{\bf W}$.
Definition 8.3. Let $\underline{M}$ be a Weil space and $\mathbb{A}$ a Weil algebra. An $\mathbb{A}$-vector field is a section of the canonical projection $\underline{p}^{\mathbb{A}}:\underline{M}^{\mathbb{A}}\to\underline{M}$, that is, a $\mathbb{K}$-Weil law $\underline{X}:\underline{M}\to\underline{M}^{\mathbb{A}}$ such that $\underline{p}\circ\underline{X}=\underline{\mathrm{id}}_{M}$.
Definition 3.7. The bundle $T^{\mathbb{A}}M:=M^{\mathbb{A}}$ over $M$ will be called the $\mathbb{A}$-tangent bundle of $M$, and $T^{\mathbb{A}}f:=f^{\mathbb{A}}$ the $\mathbb{A}$-tangent map of $f$. The fiber of $M^{\mathbb{A}}$ over $x\in M$ will often be denoted by $T_{x}^{\mathbb{A}}M:=(M^{\mathbb{A}})_{x},$ and the map between the fibers over $x$ and $f(x)$ by $T_{x}^{\mathbb{A}}f:T_{x}^{\mathbb{A}}M\to T_{f(x)}^{\mathbb{A}}N.$ These maps preserve origins in fibers; we write $0_{x}$ or $\zeta(x)$ for the origin in $T_{x}^{\mathbb{A}}M$. When $\mathbb{A}=T\mathbb{K}$, the ring of dual numbers over $\mathbb{K}$, then we simply write $TM$ and $Tf$ and just call them tangent bundle, resp. tangent map of $f$.
Definition 5.4. A $\mathbb{K}$-Weil manifold (with atlas) is a functor from the category of Weil algebras into the category of set-theoretic manifolds; in other words, it is a Weil space $\underline{M}$ together with an atlas $\underline{\mathcal{A}}=(\underline{U}_{i},\underline{\phi}_{i},\underline{V}_% {i})_{i\in I}$ modelled on some $\mathbb{K}$-module $V$, i.e., for each $\mathbb{K}$-Weil algebra $\mathbb{A}$, ${\mathcal{A}}^{\mathbb{A}}$ is an $\mathbb{A}$-atlas on $M^{\mathbb{A}}$ with model space $V^{\mathbb{A}}$. A law of Weil manifolds is a natural transformation of Weil manifolds.
Definition 3.2. Replacing the category $\underline{\mathrm{Walg}}_{\mathbb{K}}$ by some other category of $\mathbb{K}$-algebras, we may define categories of “stronger” or “weaker” Weil spaces. For instance, taking $\underline{\mathrm{Walg}}_{\mathbb{K}}^{k}$ (Weil algebras of height at most $k$), we get a weaker category of “$k$ times differentiable Weil spaces”, and taking the full category of (free and finite dimensional) commutative $\mathbb{K}$-algebras, we get ‘‘algebraic Weil spaces’’.2R. Lavendhomme ([La87], p. 195, referring to Kock [Ko77]) considers this category as a very simple, but logically satisfying model for the axiomatic setting of synthetic differential gometry.
Definition 7.4. A Weil variety with binary (ternary) multiplication is a Weil variety $\underline{M}$ together with a binary or ternary Weil law $\underline{\mu}:\underline{M}\times\underline{M}\to\underline{M}$, resp. $\underline{\mu}:\underline{M}\times\underline{M}\times\underline{M}\to% \underline{M}$. Morphisms are Weil laws compatible with the respective multiplication laws.
Definition 4.3. Let $V$ be a $\mathbb{K}$-module. A domain in $\underline{V}$ is the Weil space $\underline{U}$ given by a non-empty subset $U\subset V$: to $\mathbb{A}$, it assigns the subset of $V^{\mathbb{A}}$ defined by $U^{\mathbb{A}}:=U\times(V\otimes_{\mathbb{K}}{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}})=U\times V% ^{{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}}\subset V^{\mathbb{A}}=V\times V^{{\mathring{\mathbb% {A}}}}$ and to a morphism $\phi:\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{B}$ the restriction of $\mathrm{id}\otimes\phi$ from $U^{\mathbb{A}}$ to $U^{\mathbb{B}}$.
Definition 2.4. An ideal of a bundle (resp. Weil) algebra $\mathbb{A}=\mathbb{K}\oplus{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}$ is an ideal $\mathbb{I}$ of $\mathbb{A}$ contained in ${\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}$ that is free as $\mathbb{K}$-module and admits some free $\mathbb{K}$-module complement $C$. Note that $\mathbb{A}/\mathbb{I}$ then is again a bundle (or Weil) algebra, and so is $\hat{\mathbb{I}}:=\mathbb{K}\oplus\mathbb{I}.$ We then say that the following is a short exact sequence of Weil or bundle algebras: $\begin{matrix}0&\to&\hat{\mathbb{I}}&\to&\mathbb{A}&\to&\mathbb{A}/\mathbb{I}&% \to&0\end{matrix}.$ The sequence (2.2) is exact, and the vertical bundle algebra of $\mathbb{A}\otimes\mathbb{B}$ is its kernel: $\mathbb{A}\odot_{\mathbb{K}}\mathbb{B}:=\mathbb{A}\odot\mathbb{B}:=\widehat{{% \mathring{\mathbb{A}}}\otimes_{\mathbb{K}}{\mathring{\mathbb{B}}}}=({\mathring% {\mathbb{A}}}\otimes_{\mathbb{K}}{\mathring{\mathbb{B}}})\oplus\mathbb{K},$ Finally, a vector ideal is an ideal $\mathbb{I}$ acting as zero on ${\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}$: $\forall a\in{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}$, $\forall i\in\mathbb{I}$: $ai=0$.
Definition 2.1. (1) A scalar extension of $\mathbb{K}$ is an associative commutative unital $\mathbb{K}$-algebra $\mathbb{A}$, or, in other words, a morphism $\phi:\mathbb{K}\to\mathbb{A}$ of unital commutative rings. Scalar extensions of $\mathbb{K}$ form a category $\underline{\mathrm{Alg}}_{\mathbb{K}}$, morphisms being $\mathbb{K}$-algebra homomorphisms. (2) A $\mathbb{K}$-bundle algebra is an associative unital $\mathbb{K}$-algebra of the form $\mathbb{A}=\mathbb{K}\oplus{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}$ where $\mathbb{K}=\mathbb{K}1$ and ${\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}$ is an ideal of $\mathbb{A}$, called the fiber of $\mathbb{A}$, which is assumed to be free and finite-dimensional as a $\mathbb{K}$-module. Morphisms of bundle algebras are algebra homomorphisms preserving fibers. $\mathbb{K}$-bundle algebras form a category denoted by $\underline{\mathrm{Balg}}_{\mathbb{K}}$. (3) A $\mathbb{K}$-Weil algebra is a commutative bundle algebra such that the fiber ${\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}$ is a nilpotent ideal, called the ideal of infinitesimals. $\mathbb{K}$-Weil algebras form a category denoted by $\mathrm{Walg}_{\mathbb{K}}$, morphisms being bundle algebra morphisms. (4) The height of a Weil algebra $\mathbb{A}$ is the smallest natural number $k$ such that ${\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}^{k+1}=0$. Weil algebras of height $\leq k$ form a category denoted by $\underline{\mathrm{Walg}}_{\mathbb{K}}^{k}$. (5) A Weil algebra $\mathbb{A}$ is called a vector algebra if it is of height one, i.e., if the ideal of infinitesimals has zero product: $\forall a,b\in{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}$: $ab=0$.
Definition 6.2. A Weil variety is a Weil space $\underline{M}$ such that, for each pair $(\mathbb{A},\mathbb{B})$ of Weil algebras, resp. for each Weil ideal $\mathbb{I}$ of $\mathbb{A}$, (1) the natural map $p^{\mathbb{A},\mathbb{B}}$ is a bijection, (2) the exact algebra sequence $\hat{\mathbb{I}}\to\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{A}/\mathbb{I}$ induces an exact bundle sequence. The bundle $M^{{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}\odot{\mathring{\mathbb{B}}}}:=M^{{\mathring{\mathbb% {A}}}\oplus{\mathring{\mathbb{B}}}\oplus\mathbb{K}}$ over $M$ is called the verticle bundle with respect to $(\mathbb{A},\mathbb{B})$. Combining (1) and (2), we get an exact sequence over $M$ $\begin{matrix}M^{\mathbb{A}\odot\mathbb{B}}&\to&M^{\mathbb{A}\otimes_{\mathbb{% K}}\mathbb{B}}&\to&M^{\mathbb{A}}\times_{M}M^{\mathbb{B}}.\end{matrix}$ If $\mathbb{A}=\mathbb{B}=T\mathbb{K}$, then there is is a canonical isomorphism of Weil algebras, $T\mathbb{K}\to T\mathbb{K}\odot T\mathbb{K}=\mathbb{K}\oplus(\varepsilon_{1}% \mathbb{K}\otimes_{\mathbb{K}}\varepsilon_{2}\mathbb{K})=\mathbb{K}\oplus% \varepsilon_{1}\varepsilon\mathbb{K},\qquad(x+\varepsilon v)\mapsto x+% \varepsilon_{1}\varepsilon_{2}v,$ whose inverse we denote by $\nu$. It induces an isomorphism $\nu:M^{T\mathbb{K}\odot T\mathbb{K}}\to TM,$ between $TM$ and “the” vertical bundle, and we have the exact sequence $\begin{matrix}M&\to&TM&\to&TTM&\to&TM\times_{M}TM&\to&M.\end{matrix}$
Definition 3.3. The direct product $\underline{M}\times\underline{N}$ of two Weil spaces is defined by $\forall\mathbb{A}\in\underline{\mathrm{Walg}}_{\mathbb{K}}:\qquad(M\times N)^{% \mathbb{A}}:=M^{\mathbb{A}}\times N^{\mathbb{A}},$ and the direct product of Weil laws $\underline{f}\times\underline{g}$ is defined similarly.
Definition 7.5. A Weil Lie torsor3Besides “torsor””, other existing terminology is: groud, heap, pregroup,…, cf. [BeKi09]. is a Weil variety $\underline{G}$ together with a Weil law $\underline{\mu}:\underline{G}^{3}\to\underline{G}$, such that, for each Weil algebra $\mathbb{A}$, writing $(xyz)^{\mathbb{A}}$ instead of $\mu^{\mathbb{A}}(x,y,z)$, (1) $\forall x,y\in G^{\mathbb{A}}$: $(xxy)^{\mathbb{A}}=y=(yxx)^{\mathbb{A}}$, (2) $\forall x,y,u,v,w\in G^{\mathbb{A}}$: $(xy(uvw)^{\mathbb{A}})^{\mathbb{A}})=((xyu)^{\mathbb{A}}vw)^{\mathbb{A}})=(x(% vuy)^{\mathbb{A}}w)^{\mathbb{A}}$.
Definition 2.2. For any bundle algebra $\mathbb{A}=\mathbb{K}\oplus{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}$, the projection $\pi:\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{K}$ is a morphism with kernel ${\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}$, called the projection onto the base ring, and the natural injection $\zeta:\mathbb{K}\to\mathbb{A}$ is a morphism called the zero section. Thus $\mathbb{A}$ is a ring extension of $\mathbb{K}$, via the zero section, but $\mathbb{K}$ is also a ring “extension” of $\mathbb{A}$, via the projection. However, we will rather say that $\mathbb{K}$ is obtained from $\mathbb{A}$ by scalar restriction.
Definition 3.1. A $\mathbb{K}$-Weil space is a covariant functor $\underline{M}:\underline{\mathrm{Walg}}_{\mathbb{K}}\to\underline{\mathrm{set}% },\quad\mathbb{A}\mapsto M^{\mathbb{A}},\phi\mapsto M^{\phi}.$ A morphism between $\mathbb{K}$-Weil spaces $\underline{M}$ and $\underline{N}$, also called $\mathbb{K}$-Weil law, is a natural transformation $\underline{f}:\underline{M}\to\underline{N}.$ In other words, for each $\mathbb{A}\in\underline{\mathrm{Walg}}_{\mathbb{K}}$, there are mappings $f^{\mathbb{A}}:M^{\mathbb{A}}\to N^{\mathbb{A}}$ varying functorially with $\mathbb{A}$: for any Weil algebra morphism $\phi:\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{B}$ and Weil spaces $\underline{M},\underline{N}$, there are maps $M^{\phi}$, $N^{\phi}$ such that the following diagram commutes: $\begin{matrix}M^{\mathbb{A}}&\buildrel f^{\mathbb{A}}\over{\longrightarrow}&N^% {\mathbb{A}}\cr M^{\phi}\downarrow&&\phantom{M_{f}}\downarrow N^{\phi}\cr M^{% \mathbb{B}}&\buildrel f^{\mathbb{B}}\over{\longrightarrow}&N^{\mathbb{B}}\end{matrix}$ Weil spaces and Weil laws over $\mathbb{K}$ become a category, denoted by $\underline{\underline{\mathrm{Wsp}}}_{\mathbb{K}}$, if we define the composition $\underline{g}\circ\underline{f}$ of two $\mathbb{K}$-Weil laws $\underline{f}:\underline{M}\to\underline{N}$, $g:\underline{N}\to\underline{P}$ by $\forall\mathbb{A}\in\mathrm{Walg}_{\mathbb{K}}:\qquad(\underline{g}\circ% \underline{f})^{\mathbb{A}}:=g^{\mathbb{A}}\circ f^{\mathbb{A}}:M^{\mathbb{A}}% \to P^{\mathbb{A}}.$ Isomorphisms and automorphisms in the category of Weil spaces will be called Weil isomorphisms, resp. Weil automorphisms.
Definition 7.1. A Weil Lie group is a group object in the category of Weil varieties: it is given by $(\underline{G},\underline{m},\underline{i},\underline{e})$ where $\underline{G}$ is a Weil variety, and Weil laws $\underline{m}:\underline{G}\times\underline{G}\to\underline{G}$ and $\underline{i}:\underline{G}\to\underline{G}$ and $\underline{e}:\underline{0}\to\underline{G}$ (so $e^{\mathbb{A}}\in G^{\mathbb{A}}$ is a distinguished element) such that for each Weil algebra $\mathbb{A}$, we have a group $(G^{\mathbb{A}},m^{\mathbb{A}},i^{\mathbb{A}},e^{\mathbb{A}})$. A law of Weil Lie groups is a natural transformation $\underline{f}$ between two Weil Lie groups $\underline{G},\underline{H}$: thus $f^{\mathbb{A}}:G^{\mathbb{A}}\to H^{\mathbb{A}}$ is a group homomorphism, for all $\mathbb{A}$. We say that $\underline{G}$ is a Weil-Lie goup with atlas if it is also a Weil manifold such that the group laws are morphisms of Weil manifolds.
Definition 4.2. Let $V$ be a $\mathbb{K}$-module. The canonical trivialization of the Weil space $\underline{V}$ is given by the decomposition, for each Weil algebra $\mathbb{A}$, $V^{\mathbb{A}}=V\otimes(\mathbb{K}\oplus{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}})=V\oplus(V% \otimes{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}})=:V\oplus V^{\mathring{\mathbb{A}}}.$
Definition 8.1. Let $\underline{M}$ be a Weil space and $\mathbb{A}$ a Weil algebra. An infinitesimal endomorphism of the Weil bundle $\underline{M}^{\mathbb{A}}$ is an $\mathbb{A}$-endomorphism $\underline{F}:\underline{M}^{\mathbb{A}}\to\underline{M}^{\mathbb{A}}$ preserving fibers over $\underline{M}$, that is, such that $\underline{p}^{\mathbb{A}}\circ\underline{F}=\underline{p}^{\mathbb{A}}$. It is called an infinitesimal automorphism if, moreover, it is an automorphism of $\underline{M}^{\mathbb{A}}$. Obviously, the infinitesimal automorphisms form a group, which we denote by ${\mathrm{Infaut}}_{\mathbb{A}}(\underline{M}^{\mathbb{A}})$.
Definition 5.2. A morphism of set theoretic manifolds $(M,{\mathcal{A}})$, $(N,{\mathcal{A}}^{\prime})$ is an atlas-continuous map $f:M\to N$, i.e., a map which is continuous with respect to the atlas-topologies on $M$ and $N$.
Definition 3.5. The underlying set of a $\mathbb{K}$-Weil space $\underline{M}$ is the set $M:=M^{\mathbb{K}}$, and the underlying map of a $\mathbb{K}$-Weil law $\underline{f}:\underline{M}\to\underline{N}$ is the map $f:=f^{\mathbb{K}}:M\to N$.
Definition 3.14. A refined $t$-sequence is a pair $({\mathcal{W}}(-),t_{\mathcal{W}}(-))$ where • ${\mathcal{W}}(-)$ is a poset map from ${\mathbb{Z}}$ to the poset of wide coreflective subcategories in ${\mathcal{A}}$, and • $t_{\mathcal{W}}(-)$ is a map from ${\mathbb{Z}}$ to the set of full replete subcategories of ${\mathcal{A}}$ such that $t_{\mathcal{W}}(n)$ is a tilting torsion class in ${\mathcal{W}}(n)\cap{}^{\perp}{\mathcal{W}}(n-1)$. We denote by $\Delta({\mathcal{A}})$ the set of all refined $t$-sequences of ${\mathcal{A}}$.
Definition 2.10. Let ${\mathcal{A}}$ be an abelian category and let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a full additive subcategory of ${\mathcal{A}}$ or $D^{b}{\mathcal{A}}$. An object $E\in{\mathcal{C}}$ is called Ext-projective in ${\mathcal{C}}$ or ${\mathcal{C}}$-projective if $\operatorname{Ext}^{i}(E,C)=0$ for all $i>0$ and all $C\in{\mathcal{C}}$. The category of ${\mathcal{C}}$-projective objects is the smallest full subcategory of ${\mathcal{C}}$ containing all ${\mathcal{C}}$-projective objects.
Definition 4.6. The category $D^{b}(\operatorname{mod}\Lambda)$ is called discrete if for every function $v:{\mathbb{Z}}\to K_{0}(\operatorname{mod}\Lambda)$, there are only finitely many isomorphism classes $X\in D^{b}(\operatorname{mod}\Lambda)$ such that $[H^{i}(X)]=v(i)\in K_{0}(\operatorname{mod}\Lambda)$ for all $i\in{\mathbb{Z}}$. We will call such an algebra $\Lambda$ derived discrete.
Definition 2.13. Let ${\mathcal{E}}\subseteq D^{b}{\mathcal{A}}$ be a full additive subcategory. We will say that ${\mathcal{E}}$ is a partial silting subcategory if $\operatorname{Hom}(E,F[n])=0$ for all $E,F\in{\mathcal{E}}$ and all $n>0$. The partial silting subcategory ${\mathcal{E}}$ is called a silting subcategory if $\operatorname{thick}({\mathcal{E}})=D^{b}{\mathcal{A}}$. An object $E\in D^{b}{\mathcal{A}}$ is called a (partial) silting object if the category $\operatorname{add}(E)$ is a (partial) silting subcategory. Similarly, we will say that the subcategory ${\mathcal{E}}$ is a partial tilting subcategory if $\operatorname{Hom}(E,F[n])=0$ for all $E,F\in{\mathcal{E}}$ and all $n\not=0$. The partial tilting subcategory ${\mathcal{E}}$ is called a tilting subcategory if $\operatorname{thick}({\mathcal{E}})=D^{b}{\mathcal{A}}$. An object $E\in D^{b}{\mathcal{A}}$ is called a (partial) tilting object if the category $\operatorname{add}(E)$ is a (partial) tilting subcategory.
Definition 9.8. Let $X\in{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}$. A morphism $f\colon a\rightarrow b$ in $X$ is called a cat equivalence if $\eta_{X}\colon X\rightarrow\tau(X)$, the unit of the reflector $\tau\colon{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}\rightarrow\mathrm{Cat}$, maps f to an equivalence in the strict cat $\tau(X)$.
Definition 5.3. Define $\mathrm{Cat}\subset{\mathrm{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{\begin{sideways}$% \trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}$ to be the full subcategory generated by the cats, and define $\mathrm{Cat}^{\mathrm{strict}}\subset\mathrm{Cat}$ to be the full subcategory generated by the strict cats.
Definition 7.3. Define ${\color[rgb]{1,0,0}\mathbf{Cat^{strict}}}\subset{\color[rgb]{1,0,0}\mathbf{Cat% }}\subset{\color[rgb]{1,0,0}{\mathbf{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{% \begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}}$ to be the full $\trianglerighteqslant$ -simplicial subsets generated by the cats or by the strict cats, respectively. Define ${\color[rgb]{1,0,0}\mathbf{Grpd^{strict}}}\subset{\color[rgb]{1,0,0}\mathbf{% Grpd}}\subset{\color[rgb]{1,0,0}{\mathbf{Set}_{\tiny{\raisebox{-1.0pt}{% \begin{sideways}$\trianglerighteqslant$\end{sideways}}}}}}$ to be the full $\trianglerighteqslant$ -simplicial subsets generated by the groupoids or by the strict groupoids, respectively.
